They mark a state update as a **non-urgent transition** so React can render it in an *interruptible, lower-priority* pass instead of blocking the main thread. Urgent updates (typing, clicks) can preempt an in-progress transition render, keeping input responsive while a heavy re-render happens in the background.

Under the hood this relies on **concurrent rendering**: React prepares the new tree in memory and can pause, abandon, or restart that work if a higher-priority update arrives. `useTransition` additionally returns an `isPending` flag so you can show a subtle indicator.

```jsx
const [isPending, startTransition] = useTransition();
function onChange(e) {
  setQuery(e.target.value);            // urgent: keep the input snappy
  startTransition(() => {
    setResults(filter(e.target.value)); // non-urgent: can be interrupted
  });
}
```

Key nuance: transitions don't make code *faster* ŌĆö they change *scheduling priority* so an expensive render never blocks user input.

`use()` reads the value of a resource ŌĆö a **Promise** or a **Context** ŌĆö during render. Unlike every other hook, it may be called **conditionally** and inside loops or `if` blocks.

Given a pending Promise, `use()` **suspends** the component, integrating with the nearest `<Suspense>` boundary; when the promise resolves React re-renders with the value. It's the primitive behind first-class data fetching in the Suspense/RSC model.

```jsx
function Comment({ commentPromise }) {
  const comment = use(commentPromise);  // suspends until resolved
  return <p>{comment.text}</p>;
}
```

For context, `use(MyContext)` behaves like `useContext` but without the call-position restriction.

An **Effect Event** lets you extract the *non-reactive* part of an Effect so it can read the **latest** props/state without becoming a dependency that re-triggers the Effect.

A normal Effect re-runs whenever any value it reads changes. Sometimes you want to read the freshest value but *not* re-run ŌĆö e.g., when a chat connects, log the *current* room, but don't reconnect just because an unrelated `theme` changed.

```jsx
const onConnected = useEffectEvent(() => {
  showToast('Connected to ' + roomId, theme); // always reads latest theme
});
useEffect(() => {
  const conn = createConnection(roomId);
  conn.on('connected', onConnected);
  return () => conn.close();
}, [roomId]); // theme is NOT a dependency
```

It cleanly splits *reactive* values (in the deps array) from *non-reactive* reads. (Still experimental as of React 18/19 canaries.)

Every render creates fresh closures (event handlers, effects, timers) that **capture that render's** props and state. If an async callback or interval set up in one render runs later, it reads the *captured* (old) values ŌĆö a **stale closure**.

There are three correct fixes, depending on intent:

- Add the value to the Effect's **dependency array** so the effect re-subscribes with fresh values.
- Use the **functional updater** `setX(prev => prev + 1)` so you never read stale state.
- Store the latest value in a **ref** (`ref.current = value`) and read `ref.current` inside the long-lived callback when you specifically want the newest value without re-subscribing.

```jsx
useEffect(() => {
  const id = setInterval(() => setCount(c => c + 1), 1000); // no stale read
  return () => clearInterval(id);
}, []);
```

The bug is always about *which render's closure is still alive* ŌĆö pick the fix that matches whether you want to re-run or just read fresh.

`forwardRef` lets a parent pass a ref through to a child's DOM node or instance. `useImperativeHandle` **customizes what that ref exposes** ŌĆö instead of the raw DOM, you expose a curated imperative API.

```jsx
const TextInput = forwardRef(function TextInput(props, ref) {
  const inputRef = useRef(null);
  useImperativeHandle(ref, () => ({
    focus: () => inputRef.current.focus(),
    clear: () => { inputRef.current.value = ''; },
  }));
  return <input ref={inputRef} {...props} />;
});
```

Use it **sparingly** ŌĆö imperative handles break the declarative model ŌĆö but they're the right tool for focus management, animations, media controls, scroll control, or wrapping an imperative third-party library, where there's no clean declarative prop to express the action.

When a stateful component re-renders, it re-renders the JSX *it* creates ŌĆö but elements passed **into** it as props (notably `children`) were created by its *parent* and don't re-render just because the stateful component's state changed. Their reference is stable across that component's updates.

So you can isolate frequent state changes by **lifting the expensive subtree up** and passing it as `children`:

```jsx
function Toggle({ children }) {
  const [open, setOpen] = useState(false);   // changes often
  return <div onClick={() => setOpen(o => !o)}>{open && <Panel/>}{children}</div>;
}
// <Toggle><ExpensiveTree/></Toggle>  -> ExpensiveTree does NOT re-render on toggle
```

This often replaces a `React.memo` wrapper entirely ŌĆö composition is a cheaper, structural fix than memoization.

Async effects can resolve **out of order** or **after unmount**, causing stale UI or memory leaks. Guard them with an **ignore flag** or an **`AbortController`**, applied in the effect's cleanup:

```jsx
useEffect(() => {
  let active = true;
  fetchResults(query).then(data => {
    if (active) setResults(data);   // ignore superseded responses
  });
  return () => { active = false; }; // cleanup on re-run / unmount
}, [query]);
```

Each time `query` changes, the previous effect's cleanup flips `active = false`, so an older, slower request can't overwrite newer data. For real cancellation use `AbortController` and `controller.abort()` in cleanup. Always return a cleanup function from effects that start async work or subscriptions.

Wrap the expensive update in a **transition** (`startTransition` / `useTransition`). During a transition React keeps showing the **current** committed UI while it renders the next state in the background ŌĆö so a `<Suspense>` boundary that has *already* shown content won't drop back to its fallback spinner if the new content re-suspends.

Use the `isPending` flag to show a subtle inline indicator instead of a jarring **content ŌåÆ spinner ŌåÆ content** flash:

```jsx
const [isPending, startTransition] = useTransition();
function navigate(tab) {
  startTransition(() => setTab(tab)); // old tab stays visible until new one is ready
}
```

Pair it with `useDeferredValue` when the expensive part is a *derived* view of a fast-changing value.

**Actions** are React 19's first-class way to run async work inside a transition. An async function passed to `startTransition` ŌĆö or directly to a `<form action={fn}>` ŌĆö automatically gets managed **pending state, error handling, optimistic updates, and ordering**, so you stop hand-rolling `useState` for loading/error flags.

A form's `action` receives the `FormData` and runs as a transition; React keeps the UI responsive, tracks `isPending`, and resets the form on success:

```jsx
function ChangeName() {
  const [error, submitAction, isPending] = useActionState(
    async (prevState, formData) => {
      const err = await updateName(formData.get('name'));
      if (err) return err;       // returned value becomes the next state
      redirect('/profile');
      return null;
    },
    null,
  );
  return (
    <form action={submitAction}>
      <input name="name" />
      <button disabled={isPending}>Save</button>
      {error && <p>{error}</p>}
    </form>
  );
}
```

Actions also enable **progressive enhancement** ŌĆö a form with an action can submit before JS hydrates.

`useFormStatus` lets a component read the submission status of the **nearest parent `<form>`** ŌĆö `{ pending, data, method, action }` ŌĆö without the form passing props down. It exists for **design-system components** that need to react to submission state but live deep inside a form.

The canonical use is a reusable submit button that disables itself while the form is submitting:

```jsx
import { useFormStatus } from 'react-dom';
function SubmitButton() {
  const { pending } = useFormStatus();
  return <button disabled={pending}>{pending ? 'SavingŌĆ”' : 'Save'}</button>;
}
```

It must be called from a component rendered *inside* the `<form>` (it reads the form context), not from the component that renders the form itself.

`useOptimistic` renders an **optimistic** version of state immediately while an async action runs, then automatically reconciles to the real state when the action settles (and reverts cleanly if it fails). It's ideal for likes, sending a message, or toggles where you don't want to wait for the server.

```jsx
const [optimisticMsgs, addOptimistic] = useOptimistic(
  messages,
  (current, newMsg) => [...current, { ...newMsg, sending: true }],
);
async function send(formData) {
  addOptimistic({ text: formData.get('text') }); // shows instantly
  await sendMessage(formData);                    // real state catches up
}
```

React discards the optimistic value once the underlying state updates, so you never manually roll back ŌĆö the base state becomes the source of truth again.

In React 19, **function components can accept `ref` as an ordinary prop** ŌĆö `forwardRef` is no longer required and is deprecated for future removal. You just destructure `ref` like any other prop:

```jsx
function MyInput({ ref, ...props }) {
  return <input ref={ref} {...props} />;
}
// <MyInput ref={inputRef} />
```

React 19 also lets a **ref callback return a cleanup function**, which runs when the element unmounts ŌĆö instead of the callback being invoked again with `null`:

```jsx
<div ref={(node) => {
  const observer = observe(node);
  return () => observer.disconnect(); // cleanup on unmount
}} />
```

Together these simplify ref-forwarding components and make imperative setup/teardown symmetric.

React 19 natively supports rendering `<title>`, `<meta>`, and `<link>` tags **anywhere** in your component tree; React automatically **hoists** them into the document `<head>`. This removes the need for libraries like react-helmet for basic per-page metadata.

```jsx
function BlogPost({ post }) {
  return (
    <article>
      <title>{post.title}</title>
      <meta name="description" content={post.excerpt} />
      <link rel="canonical" href={post.url} />
      <h1>{post.title}</h1>
    </article>
  );
}
```

It works with SSR and streaming, so per-page titles and SEO tags are emitted in the right place without extra dependencies.

React 19 exposes resource hints from `react-dom` so you can tell the browser to fetch things early and improve load performance. React dedupes calls and emits the corresponding `<link>` tags in the right order:

- `preload(href, { as })` ŌĆö download a resource (font, stylesheet, image) you'll need soon.
- `preinit(href, { as })` ŌĆö download **and** evaluate it (e.g., eagerly load + run a stylesheet or script).
- `prefetchDNS(href)` ŌĆö resolve a domain's DNS ahead of time.
- `preconnect(href)` ŌĆö open a connection to an origin before requesting from it.

```jsx
import { preinit, preload, preconnect } from 'react-dom';
preconnect('https://cdn.example.com');
preload('/fonts/inter.woff2', { as: 'font' });
preinit('/theme.css', { as: 'style' });
```

Calling them during render (or in an event) lets React schedule the hints optimally instead of you hand-writing `<link rel>` tags.

**Server Actions** are async functions marked with the `"use server"` directive that execute on the **server** but can be **called from client components** or passed to a form's `action`. React handles the RPC ŌĆö serializing the arguments, invoking the function on the server, and returning the result ŌĆö so you can do mutations (DB writes, revalidation) without hand-writing an API route.

```jsx
// actions.js
'use server';
export async function addTodo(formData) {
  await db.todo.create({ text: formData.get('text') });
}
```
```jsx
// a client component
import { addTodo } from './actions';
<form action={addTodo}><input name="text" /></form>
```

They're distinct from **Server Components** (which *render* on the server): a Server Action is a *callable* function. Combined with Actions/`useActionState`, they give forms pending state, errors, and progressive enhancement.
